5. The Making and Breaking of Marital Bonds in Modern Egypt -- t16. Artists and Entrepreneurs: Female Singers in Cairo during the 1920s -- t17. Biography and Women's History: On Interpreting Doria Shafik -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis history of Middle Eastern women is the first to survey gender relations in the Middle East from the earliest Islamic period to the present. Outstanding scholars analyze a rich array of sources ranging from histories, biographical dictionaries, law books, prescriptive treatises, and archival records, to the Traditions (hadith) of the Prophet and imaginative works like the Thousand and One Nights, to modern writings by Middle Eastern women and by Western writers. They show that gender boundaries in the Middle East have been neither fixed nor immutable: changes in family patterns, religious rituals, socio-economic necessity, myth and ideology-and not least, women’s attitudes-have expanded or circumscribed women’s roles and behavior through the ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminismzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aWomenzMiddle EastxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aAbadan-Unat, Nermin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmed, Leila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaron, Beth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaron, Beth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerkey, Jonathan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy-Smith, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanielson, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c